## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design secure cross-account event-driven data flows at scale, including least privilege IAM, cross-account trust, private networking, and centralized audit controls.

## Key Concepts

- Cross-account roles and trust policies (A→B→C)
- Private connectivity: VPC endpoints and PrivateLink
- KMS CMK rotation and key grants
- Immutable audit via CloudTrail and S3 Object Lock, drift detection

## Code Example

```javascript
// Node.js pseudo-example: assume role to access Account C S3 with KMS
const { STSClient, AssumeRoleCommand } = require("@aws-sdk/client-sts");
const { S3Client, PutObjectCommand } = require("@aws-sdk/client-s3");

async function writeToCrossAccountS3(data) {
  // Assume role in Account C
  const sts = new STSClient({});
  const assumeRoleResponse = await sts.send(new AssumeRoleCommand({
    RoleArn: process.env.ACCOUNT_C_S3_ROLE_ARN,
    RoleSessionName: 'kinesis-lambda-session'
  }));

  // Use temporary credentials to access Account C S3
  const s3 = new S3Client({
    credentials: {
      accessKeyId: assumeRoleResponse.Credentials.AccessKeyId,
      secretAccessKey: assumeRoleResponse.Credentials.SecretAccessKey,
      sessionToken: assumeRoleResponse.Credentials.SessionToken
    }
  });

  await s3.send(new PutObjectCommand({
    Bucket: process.env.TARGET_S3_BUCKET,
    Key: `events/${Date.now()}.json`,
    Body: JSON.stringify(data),
    ServerSideEncryption: 'aws:kms',
    SSEKMSKeyId: process.env.SECURITY_ACCOUNT_CMK_ARN
  }));
}
```

